        "source_parser": "structured_abstract",
        "target_id": "paper-section-2-methods",
        "target_kind": "section",
        "target_page": null,
        "text_content": "A comprehensive search was undertaken among the four major databases (PubMed, Embase, Scopus, and Ovid) to identify all published data comparing open vs endovascular repair in management of acute type B aortic dissection. Databases where evaluated and assessed to July 2017. The 95% confidence intervals were analyzed from the extracted data using relevant statistical methods."
      },
      {
        "bounding_boxes": [],
        "canonical_map": "results",
        "confidence": null,
        "id": "outline-node-paper-section-3-results",
        "is_collapsible": false,
        "is_generated_heading": false,
        "label_normalized": "Results",
        "label_original": "Results",
        "level": 2,
        "node_type": "section",
        "order_index": 3,
        "page_end": null,
        "page_start": null,
        "parent_id": "outline-group-main_text",
        "section_type": "canonical",
        "source_parser": "structured_abstract",
        "target_id": "paper-section-3-results",
        "target_kind": "section",
        "target_page": null,
        "text_content": "Overall, 18,193 patients were found in a combination of nine studies. Patients undergoing open repair were younger (mean, 61.3 \u00b1 9.3 years vs 66.6 \u00b1 12.5 years; P <.00001). Postoperative stroke and paraplegia were similar in both groups (P =.71 and P =.81 respectively); however, the rate of all neurologic complications were more common in the traditional open repair group (6.9% vs 4.8%; P =.006). The all-cause operative and 1-year death was reported as higher in the open repair group (18.6% vs 7.4% [P <.0001] and 24.3% vs 14.3% [P <.0001], respectively); however, at 5 years this rate is almost similar between both groups (46.7% vs 49.7%; P =.21). At 1 year, the rate of reintervention was reported to be higher in endovascular repair group of patients (15.4% vs 5.5%; P =.004)."
      },
      {
        "bounding_boxes": [],
        "canonical_map": "conclusions",
        "confidence": null,
        "id": "outline-node-paper-section-4-conclusions",
        "is_collapsible": false,
        "is_generated_heading": false,
        "label_normalized": "Conclusions",
        "label_original": "Conclusions",
        "level": 2,
        "node_type": "section",
        "order_index": 4,
        "page_end": null,
        "page_start": null,
        "parent_id": "outline-group-main_text",
        "section_type": "canonical",
        "source_parser": "structured_abstract",
        "target_id": "paper-section-4-conclusions",
        "target_kind": "section",
        "target_page": null,
        "text_content": "This study concludes that endovascular repair, in the setting of acute type B thoracic aortic dissection, provides an early surgical benefit; however, this finding has not yet been supported by long-term data. There seems to be a benefit with respect to all-neurologic events in favor of endovascular repair. Long-term comparative data and studies are required to give a better understanding of these two approaches."
      },
